## 3. Common Layouts and Their Trade-offs

### 3.1 Fixed Aspect Ratio Grids

<!-- TODO: Develop prose -->

The simplest approach: force all photos into the same aspect ratio.

```css
.gallery {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(200px, 1fr));
  gap: 0.5rem;
}

.gallery img {
  aspect-ratio: 1 / 1; /* or 4/5, 3/2, etc. */
  object-fit: cover;
}
```

![Square grid illustration](./assets/square-grid.svg "Fixed aspect ratio grid — all photos cropped to squares")

**Trade-off:** Maximum space efficiency, strong visual rhythm, but **crops composition**. Photos are forced into a shape they weren't composed for.

#### Rhythm: Perfect in Both Directions

In a fixed aspect ratio grid, all photos have identical dimensions. Vertical gaps align perfectly across rows, forming vertical leading lines that repeat horizontally — strong **horizontal rhythm**. Horizontal gaps align perfectly across columns, forming horizontal leading lines that repeat vertically — strong **vertical rhythm**.

![Fixed aspect ratio grid with leading lines](./assets/square-grid-leading-lines.svg "Gaps form a perfect grid of horizontal and vertical guides")

With high contrast between photos and background, and sufficiently thick gaps, this perfect grid can even trigger the [Hermann grid illusion](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grid_illusion) — viewers perceive phantom dark spots at the intersections of the white gaps.

#### Cover vs. Contain

When photos don't match the target aspect ratio, there are two strategies:

**Cover (crop):** Fill the target area completely, cutting off overflow. Maximizes space efficiency and preserves rhythm, but loses content.

**Contain (fit):** Show the entire image, accepting empty space. Preserves composition, but breaks rhythm — photos appear at different sizes.

![Contain/fit approach in a square grid](./assets/square-grid-fit.svg "Photos fitted (not cropped) into square cells — the square photo dominates while others shrink")

With contain/fit, leading lines bend and break:

![Contain/fit grid with broken leading lines](./assets/square-grid-fit-leading-lines.svg "Fitted photos break the leading lines — gaps become inconsistent")

Most grids use cover/crop. The question becomes: *what* to crop?

- **Center crop** — naive default, often cuts subjects positioned using rule-of-thirds
- **Smart crop** — libraries like [smartcrop.js](https://github.com/jwagner/smartcrop.js) analyze edges, skin tones, and visual weight. No AI required — just clever, computationally cheap heuristics
- **AI-assisted crop** — services like Cloudinary detect subjects and faces. More accurate, but requires server-side processing
- **Editorial tight crop** — artistic choice where previews crop dramatically tighter than the full image, creating intrigue

#### The Aspect Ratio Change Problem

Choosing a fixed aspect ratio means committing to it. Changing later breaks existing content.

Instagram originally enforced square previews — a neutral choice that worked on both mobile and desktop. In early 2025, they shifted to portrait-oriented rectangles. For a mobile-first platform, this makes sense.

But for existing content, this was destructive. Photos composed for square display were suddenly cropped differently. Subjects intentionally placed at edges — visible in square previews — were cut off.

![Instagram — original square previews](https://share.kadykov.com/images/blog/designing-a-photo-gallery-layout/instagram-square.avif "Instagram's original square grid")

![Instagram — newer rectangular previews](https://share.kadykov.com/images/blog/designing-a-photo-gallery-layout/instagram-rectangular.avif "Portrait-oriented previews — edge content gets cropped")

The lesson: fixed aspect ratios require commitment. Changing them later harms content that was composed for the original ratio.

